[1]
Date: Mon 18 Apr 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Agence France Press report, Sun 17 Apr 2005 [edited]
<http://www.reliefweb.int/rw/RWB.NSF/db900SID/MHII-6BK3SS?OpenDocument>

Angola: Marburg death toll reaches 235
--------------------------------------
The death toll from the Marburg virus epidemic rose to 235 in Angola on Sun
17 Apr 2005, with some 500 people under surveillance after coming in
contact with the virus, the Health Ministry and the World Health
Organization (WHO) said.
Health officials are treating a total of 257 cases of [Marburg virus
infection], which has claimed 219 lives in the northern province of Uige,
the epicenter of the outbreak that was 1st detected in October [2004],
according to a statement from the Ministry and WHO. An additional 513
people are under surveillance, it added.
WHO experts said last week [3rd week April 2005] that there was no end in
sight for the epidemic, the worst outbreak ever of the virus, 1st detected
in 1967 when German laboratory workers in Marburg were infected by monkeys
from Uganda. The Marburg virus can kill a healthy person in a week by
diarrhea and vomiting followed by severe internal bleeding and is not
treatable with any known drugs.
