[2]
Date: Mon 18 Apr 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: National Post, Mon 18 Apr 2005 [edited]
<http://www.canada.com/national/nationalpost/news/comment/story.html?id=bd2a122b-b41f-4aa9-80e2-40d2f51319db>

Angola: The heroes of Uige
--------------------------
The town of Uige, Angola is witnessing an outbreak of Marburg virus
infection, one of the most deadly contagions known to humans. The incurable
Ebola-like disease causes fever, headache, nausea, and profuse bleeding.
Because it can be transmitted through contact with any bodily fluid, the
virus can spread quickly within a community. In Uige, more than 200 people
are thought to have died since the epidemic began earlier this year [2005].
This number would be far higher if not for the heroic efforts of local
health officials, as well as medical specialists from the World Health
Organization (WHO), the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, and
the charity Medecins sans Frontieres.
Angola, a war-ravaged nation with a primitive health infrastructure, is not
an especially safe place to practise medicine under normal circumstances.
But with Marburg virus on the loose, the risks are extreme. Indeed, many of
the dead are health care workers who contracted the virus while caring for
victims at local hospitals. In some cases, terrified staff have fled, and
the doctors have had to mop and decontaminate their buildings themselves.
Making matters worse is the hostility of the local population. Since so
many of the victims who've been taken into hospitals by health care workers
have died, the town has been swept up by rumors that the masked doctors in
their midst are deliberately killing patients. During a recent tour of Uige
with a New York Times reporter, a Columbian doctor was forced to abandon
his rounds when a crowd of townspeople attacked a colleague's van with sticks.
2 of the heroes are Maria Bonino, an Italian doctor working with the
Italian aid group Doctors with Africa, and Matondo Alexandre, a UN child
protection expert based in Angola. Together, the pair raised the alarm over
Marburg earlier this year [2005], broadcasting their warnings over the
radio in February, when the government wasn't yet taking the outbreak
seriously. The radio broadcast attracted the attention of Angola's health
ministry and the WHO. But tragically, Dr Bonino contracted the disease and
died, less than a week after a laboratory in Atlanta confirmed her
suspicions. Mr Alexandre has been denounced as a witch, and his aunt was
beaten by Uige residents.
There is now a large contingent of Western health officials in the Uige
area, including Dr Heinz Feldmann, a Winnipeg-based virologist. Thanks to
their efforts, the outbreak seems to have been contained.
