No evidence of Marburg fever in DRC Bas-Congo Province bordering Angola
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
A medical team deployed to the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) Bas-Congo
Province, bordering Angola, found no trace of Marburg fever in the area.
The United Nations Mission in the DRC (MONUC) Humanitarian Section took
part in a joint meeting convened by the Congolese Ministry of Health on 12
Apr 2005 in Kinshasa. The discussion focused on the results of a
fact-finding mission that was deployed to the border with Angola for
several weeks, following the outbreak of [Marburg] hemorrhagic fever,
mostly affecting the populations of the Angolan town of Uige near the
border with the DRC. The team concluded that, although the threats that
people infected by the deadly virus in Angola will enter the DRC remain
real, there are currently no signs of Marburg fever in the area. UNHCR
representatives requested that refugee camps in the DRC towns bordering
Angola be placed under strict medical surveillance.
[byline: Patrice Bogna]
